\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Malicious Code Protection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
System Administrators shall implement malicious code protection mechanisms at system entry and exit points and on all workstations,
 servers,
 and mobile devices to detect and eradicate malicious code.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Automatic Updates
\series default
:
 Malicious code protection mechanisms shall be configured to perform automatic updates of virus definitions and scanning engines at least daily.
 If automatic updates are not feasible,
 manual updates shall be performed daily.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Real-Time Scanning
\series default
:
 Mechanisms shall be configured to perform real-time scanning of files from external sources as they are downloaded,
 opened,
 or executed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Periodic Scanning
\series default
:
 Mechanisms shall perform full system scans at weekly intervals or in accordance with the schedule defined in the System Security Plan (SSP).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Response Actions
\series default
:
 Upon detection of malicious code,
 the mechanism shall automatically block or quarantine the malicious code and alert the IT Service Desk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 System Monitoring
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Department shall ensure that information systems are monitored to detect attacks and indicators of potential attacks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Monitoring Tools:
 The Department shall employ automated tools (e.g.,
 IDS/IPS,
 SIEM) to monitor inbound and outbound communications traffic for unusual or unauthorized activities or conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Perimeter Monitoring:
 Monitoring shall check for indicators of attacks and unauthorized connections at external boundaries and at key internal boundaries.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Alerting:
 System-generated security alerts shall be transmitted to the ISO and designated System Administrators in real-time.
 Personnel shall analyze and respond to alerts in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Legal Review:
 The IT Director shall consult with the District Attorney's Office to ensure that monitoring activities comply with applicable federal and state privacy laws.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Information Integrity and Input Validation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Integrity Checks
\series default
:
 System Administrators shall employ integrity verification tools (e.g.,
 File Integrity Monitoring - FIM) to detect unauthorized changes to software,
 firmware,
 and information.
 For systems processing CJI,
 integrity checks shall be performed at least weekly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Input Validation
\series default
:
 Developers and System Administrators shall ensure that information systems check the validity of information inputs (e.g.,
 character set,
 length,
 numerical range,
 format) to prevent injection attacks (e.g.,
 SQL injection,
 Cross-Site Scripting) and data corruption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Spam Protection
\series default
:
 The Department shall employ spam protection mechanisms at information system entry and exit points to detect and action unsolicited messages.
 Spam protection signatures shall be updated automatically.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Flaw Remediation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Flaw remediation (patching) shall be executed in strict accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 System Administrators shall identify,
 report,
 and correct information system flaws,
 test software updates for effectiveness and potential side effects,
 and install security-relevant updates within the timelines mandated by 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Memory Protection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
System Administrators shall ensure that operating systems and applications utilize memory protection controls (e.g.,
 Data Execution Prevention [DEP],
 Address Space Layout Randomization [ASLR]) to prevent the execution of unauthorized code.
\end_layout

